
[1]vernacular

   VERNAC'ULAR, a. [L. vernaculus, born in one's house, from verns, a
   servant.]

   1. Native; belonging to the country of one's birth. English is our
   vernacular language. The vernacular idiom is seldom perfectly acquired
   by foreigners.

   2. Native; belonging to the person by birth or nature.

   A vernacular disease, is one which prevails in a particular country or
   district; more generally called endemic.
